"This paper examines the cryptographic security of fixed versus random elliptic curves over GF(p). It assumes a precomputation for use in breaking the elliptic curve discrete logarithm problem ( ecdlp ) can be made for fixed curves. A lower bound for the efficiency of a variation of Pollard’s rho method for solving multiple ecdlp s is presented, as well as an approximation of the expected time remaining to solve an ecdlp when a given size of precomputation is available. We conclude that adding 4 bits to the order of a fixed curve to avoid general software attacks plus 6 bits to avoid attacks on curves with special properties provides equivalent security."
